User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 28, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 60 responses, 28 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 47% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

This survey appears to have a strong focus on cognitive neuroscience and clinical neuroscience/mental health. Many respondents list cognitive neuroscience as their primary area, often combined with specific techniques like fMRI, EEG, or pupillometry. There is also significant representation from areas related to:

  • Neurological disorders: Dementia, Alzheimer’s disease, Multiple Sclerosis, Stroke, Epilepsy, Brain Tumors, Neurodegenerative diseases
  • Psychiatric and mental health: Mental disorders, psychotherapy, Child and adolescent psychiatry, Integrative neuroscience of mood and psychotic disorders, Anorexia nervosa, Psychosis
  • Aging and related conditions: Healthy ageing, dementia, cerebrovascular disease, Women’s health, menopause and aging cognition
  • Specific cognitive domains: Language, Memory, Attention, Decision-making, Music Cognition, Auditory Processing, Impulse Control
  • Related techniques/methodologies: MRI (various types), Neurostimulation, Imaging, Eye-tracking, Computational Modelling, Qualitative research
  • Pain research: Neurobiology of pain, Kognisjon, behandlingsforskning, smerte
  • Other: Sexual health, Autoimmunity, Paleoclimatology

In summary, the survey respondents represent a diverse group of researchers with a strong core in cognitive and clinical neuroscience, with significant interest in neurodegenerative/neurological diseases, mental health, and aging, as well as a variety of methods and techniques used to study the brain.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

In summary, increased and more accessible MRI would significantly expand and improve research across a wide range of fields. Key benefits include:

  • Enabling new research areas: Access to MRI would allow researchers to explore brain mechanisms in areas such as sexual function, bilingualism, pain, cognition, dementia, ADHD (especially in women), the menstrual cycle, and interactions with artificial intelligence. Some researchers are unable to conduct certain research studies due to lack of access.
  • Improving existing research: Researchers currently using MRI would benefit from easier access, leading to larger sample sizes, more frequent scanning, multi-site collaborations, and improved longitudinal studies.
  • Enhancing the quality and depth of research: Researchers would be able to better understand disease progression, develop new algorithms, test reproducibility of findings, and assess treatment effects with brain imaging.
  • Advancing diagnostic capabilities: MRI is essential for developing and testing novel imaging techniques for diagnosing and monitoring diseases like epilepsy, lupus nephritis, and multiple sclerosis.
  • Boosting grant applications: Access to MRI facilities would lead to greater experience and publications, increasing funding opportunities.
  • Supporting clinical translation: MRI is crucial for bridging the gap between basic research and clinical applications, such as image-guided neurosurgery and improved diagnostic imaging.
  • Supporting research in rural areas Access to MRI is a particular challenge in rural areas of northern Norway. Increased access to equipment would allow patients to take part in multicenter studies.
  • Improving clinical interventions. MRI can assist in determining the effectiveness of clinical interventions.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Several key themes emerged from the survey responses. Researchers highlighted the need for improved access and infrastructure to facilitate MRI research. This included advocating for a dedicated research scanner located closer to the University of Bergen campus, separate from clinical demands, and ensuring consistent capabilities across different sites. Furthermore, respondents stressed the importance of prioritization of research time on scanners, potentially through adjusted pricing or dedicated research hours, and emphasized the creation of a strong, collaborative MRI research community, particularly in Tromsø. The potential benefits of an MRI scanner located outside a hospital environment, enabling innovative brain science approaches and large-scale population mapping, were also underscored, alongside a desire for advanced technology like a 7T scanner for specialized subcortical research.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this survey delivers a resounding message: the Norwegian research community urgently needs increased access to dedicated, state-of-the-art MRI scanners. The overwhelming support for this initiative, coupled with the detailed accounts of hindered research progress, highlights a critical bottleneck in our nation’s scientific potential. From pioneering new treatments for neurological disorders to unraveling the complexities of human cognition and behavior, the potential impact of improved MRI access is far-reaching and promises significant advancements across various fields.

This data underscores the necessity for strategic investment in research infrastructure. It’s not merely about acquiring more scanners, but about creating a collaborative ecosystem where researchers have reliable access, are supported by expert personnel, and can leverage cutting-edge technology to push the boundaries of knowledge. By addressing these needs, Norway can solidify its position as a leader in innovative research and ultimately improve the health and well-being of its citizens. This survey serves as a clear call to action, urging policymakers and funding bodies to prioritize the acquisition and strategic deployment of research-focused MRI scanners, unlocking the full potential of Norway’s research talent and driving transformative discoveries for years to come.
